Hombourg, Haut-Rhin, Grand Est, France","Metz, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Metz, Moselle, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Metz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a short form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i>, composed of ancient Germanic <i>maht</i> ‘might, strength’ + <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from Metz in Lorraine, which took its name from a Gaulish tribe, the <i>Mediomatrici</i>; in the name of the place this became abbreviated to <i>Mettis</i>, hence the modern name.","German: from <i>Mätz</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Matthias</i> (see   Matthew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mette","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz  ).","North German: occupational name for a miller, from Middle Low German <i>matte</i>, <i>mette</i> ‘dry measure’.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>mete</i> ‘boundary stone, boundary’ (from Latin <i>meta</i> ‘bounded estate’)."]},{"name":"Metzer","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Metz (see   Metz  ).","Dutch: occupational name for a bricklayer, Middle Dutch <i>metsere</i>."]},{"name":"Metts","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Metz  ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Metze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Gerhard, Gernot.","German:","metronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz   1)."]}]},{"name":"Clémence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval French and English form of Latin <i>Clementia</i>, a derivative of <i>Clemens</i> (  see  Clement  ) or an abstract noun meaning ‘mercy’. It was fairly popular in Britain from the late medieval period until the 17th century, but has since been used less often."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Clémence de Metz was born in 1113, in Metz, Moselle, France, her father, Folmar V de Metz, was 24 and her mother, Matilda von Dagsburg, was 18. She married Folmar I. von Blieskastel about 1163. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1179."},"et":{"1113–after 1179":"1113–pärast 1179","1113–1179":"1113–1179","1115–1180":"1115–1180","–1147":"–1147","–1157":"–1157","–1159":"–1159","–1171":"–1171","1131–1179":"1131–1179","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1150–1223":"1150–1223","1090–1145":"1090–1145","1096–1157":"1096–1157","1090":"1090","environ 1157":"umbes 1157","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1131":"1131","1174":"1174","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1180":"1180","1159":"1159","1115":"1115","1147":"1147","1113":"1113","UM 1163":"umbes 1163","1179":"1179","1223":"1223","1157":"1157","1145":"1145","after 1174":"pärast 1174","UM 1135":"umbes 1135","after 1179":"pärast 1179","Metz, Moselle, Grand Est, France":"Metz, Moselle, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Hombourg, Haut-Rhin, Großer Osten, Frankreich":"Hombourg, Haut-Rhin, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Metz, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Metz, Moselle, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1113–after 1179":"1113–1179 jälkeen","1113–1179":"1113–1179","1115–1180":"1115–1180","–1147":"–1147","–1157":"–1157","–1159":"–1159","–1171":"–1171","1131–1179":"1131–1179","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1150–1223":"1150–1223","1090–1145":"1090–1145","1096–1157":"1096–1157","1090":"1090","environ 1157":"noin 1157","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1131":"1131","1174":"1174","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1180":"1180","1159":"1159","1115":"1115","1147":"1147","1113":"1113","UM 1163":"noin 1163","1179":"1179","1223":"1223","1157":"1157","1145":"1145","after 1174":"1174 jälkeen","UM 1135":"noin 1135","after 1179":"1179 jälkeen","Metz, Moselle, Grand Est, France":"Metz, Moselle, Grand Est, Ranska","Homb